R-Fundamentals

This introduction serves as a guide to the primary concepts of the R language. First off, make sure you have installed R and RStudio. You can do everything presented here in R, but RStudio provides a nice interface with added functionality.
Base R looks like this:

The top image is the console, where your R code is executed and the results are displayed. It is possible to type commands directly into the console window. However, it is better to have all of your R code saved in a script. The bottom image is an R script (save it with extension .R).

RStudio IDE looks like this:
In RStudio, the console (bottom left) and scrpit (top left) windows are combined, and added functionality is displayed in the right pane. Note that there are also tabs for multiple scripts, which is very handy. In the bottom right pane you see tabs for Environment, History, Plots, Packages, Help and Viewer. I use the Plots and Help tabs most frequently. The top right pane shows a directory structure and files for easy access. RStudio is highly customizable. I have changed the colour of my console and script from the default. There are several colour options in RStudio ->Preferences ->Appearance. There are also many great RStudio resources, including a set of cheatsheets and reference guides that are useful when new to R and RStudio.

To create a new R script you can either go to File -> New File -> R Script, or click on the icon with the + sign in the top left of the RStudio window and select R Script. If you like keyboard shortcuts, use Command+Shift+N in MacOS (Ctrl+Shift+N in Windows). In order to execute lines of code saved in a script, you can highlight the line(s) you wish to run and then press the Run icon on the top right of your script window, or you can highlight the line(s) and use the keyboard shortcut Command+Return in MacOS (Ctrl+Enter in Windows).

Now we will go through a set of commands to learn basic R functionality. I recommend that you save them in an R script for future use, but you may also just copy and paste them directly into the console and press Return (Enter).

Using R as a Calculator
(note # is a comment in R)

# Simple operations + - * / ^
4+5 # addition
4-5 # subtraction
4*5 # multiplication
4/5 # division
4^5 # power
# Mathematical operations
sqrt(4) # square root
log(4) # natural log
log10(4) # log base 10
exp(4) # exponential
4%%5 # modulus
4%/% # integer division

Assignment Operator
There are two ways to make assignments in R, using <- or =

x<-200
x=200 # equivalent to above with <-
# look at assigned object
x
# you don't have to assign to a single letter name, and you can assign the results of an operation
seven<-5+2
seven
[1] 7

When storing more than one number to your object, combine numbers using c(). Inside the parentheses, include numbers separated by a comma. For example, we create two vectors of numbers (these vectors can also be called variables).

variable1<-c(4,10,3,2,12)
variable2<-c(1,2,3,4,5)
variable1
[1]  4 10  3  2 12

Different Ways to Create Vectors
In addition to specifying specific numbers and combining them together into a vector using c, we can create vectors of sequences or ranges of numbers with seq(), rep(), and :. Try the following:

# a sequence of numbers from 2 to 10 by increments of 2
t<-seq(2,14, by=2) 
# repeat the number 5 20 times
u<-rep(5,20)
# a range of numbers from 1 to 5
v<-1:5

Operations on Vectors
We can apply simple and more complicated mathematical operations to numbers and data vectors. For example variable1+x will return a vector with 200 added to each value of variable1. Try these vector operations:

variable1+variable2
variable3<-variable1/variable2

Be careful about your vector lengths. For example, the operation variable1*t cannot be performed because the vectors are different in length (variable has 5 elements and t has 7 elements).
Creating Matrices
Vectors can be combined into matrices using c() (combine), rbind() (row bind) and cbind() (column bind). Combining vectors with c will stack vectors in the same row, creating a concatenated vector. Combining two vectors with rbind() will create a matrix with two rows and n columns, where n is the length of the vectors. Combining two vectors with cbind() will create a matrix with two columns and n rows. Again, we must be careful about vector lengths and matrix dimensions when combining.

c(variable1,variable2)
matrix1<-rbind(variable1,variable2)
matrix2<-cbind(variable1,variable2)

Creating Data Frames
We can create a dataset from two (or more) variables using the data.frame command:

dat<-data.frame(variable1,variable2)

Note how dat is similar to matrix2 (column binding is similar to creating a data frame). The distinction between the two is the type of object that they are (matrix versus data.frame), and the subsequent properties they have. If there is any question as to whether an object is a matrix or a data frame you can use is.matrix() or is.data.frame() to check. A boolean value will be returned.

is.matrix(dat)
[1] FALSE
is.data.frame(dat)
[1] TRUE

Importing Data from External Files
We can read in an external dataset with a variety of read commands, including read.table, read.csv or read.delim. In general you can use read.table and specify whether there is a header=FALSE or header=TRUE, and the delimiter with sep="" (where you put , for comma separated, for tab separated, or a blank space for space separated delimiters). For comma separated data, read.csv is a better option as you do not need to specify the delimiter or header (it is assumed that there is a header). Some examples using these data on jogging distance and duration. Note, be sure to specify the path to wherever you saved the file to be imported.

# tab delimited
jogging.txt<-read.table("sample_data_jogging.txt", header=TRUE, sep='\t')
# comma separated
jogging<-read.csv("sample_data_jogging.csv")

Working with Data Frames
Since R is a vector/matrix based language,all data frames are stored so that they may be referenced by row and column of a matrix. Furthermore the contents of datasets, imported from an external file or created in R, can be examined using commands including summary to get summary statistics of the entire contents of the dataset, names to get the column headers of the dataset, and dim to get the dimensions of the dataset.

summary(jogging) 
   subject_id     jog_time_hrs   jog_distance_mi
 Min.   : 1.00   Min.   :0.500   Min.   : 3.00  
 1st Qu.: 3.25   1st Qu.:1.250   1st Qu.: 5.50  
 Median : 5.50   Median :2.250   Median :11.00  
 Mean   : 5.50   Mean   :2.400   Mean   :11.50  
 3rd Qu.: 7.75   3rd Qu.:3.375   3rd Qu.:14.75  
 Max.   :10.00   Max.   :5.000   Max.   :26.00  
names(jogging) 
[1] "subject_id"      "jog_time_hrs"    "jog_distance_mi"
dim(jogging) 
[1] 10  3

We see that there are 10 rows and 4 columns in the dataset. To extract one column, or a variable from our dataset, use $:

jogging$subject_id

Adding a column is done in a similar fashion, but by assignment. Below we calculate jogging speed from distance/time and add this as a column to the jogging data frame.

jogging$jog_speed_mph<-jogging$jog_distance_mi/jogging$jog_time_hrs

Since data are stored as matrices, we can also look at data in terms of specifying the row and/or column number in the form dataset[row,column].

jogging[1,] # get 1st row
jogging[,2] # get 2nd column
jogging[2,3] # get observation in row 2, column 3

Writing Data to an External File
After we have done calculations and added new columns to our data frame, we might like to save it as a .csv or .txt file. In these situations we need to use write.table() or write.csv() specifying the data frame to be written and the file name (with path) to write to. For write.table() we also must specify the delimiter. R automatically adds a row id, which I dont find particularly useful, so also include the option row.names=FALSE when saving to external files.

write.table(jogging,'jogging_new.txt', sep="\t",row.names=FALSE)
write.csv(jogging,'jogging_new.csv',row.names=FALSE)

Alternatively, if we will be using our data in R again, we may wish to save it as an R dataset .Rdata. For this we use save().

save(jogging, file='jogging_new.RData')

Lists
In addition to vectors, matrices and data frames, you can store data in lists. Basically an R list is a vector of objects. The nice thing about lists is that each of your objects in the list can be of different length or dimension. For example, we can combine a scalar, vector and matrix that we created above into a list:

x<-200
u<-rep(5,20)
matrix1<-rbind(variable1,variable2)
myList<-list(x,u,matrix1)

We can extract elements of a list with single square brackets []. For instance myList[3] will return the matrix1 portion of myList. We can extract multiple members of a list by referencing with c inside the call to the list. For example, to extract the 2nd and 3nd elements of myList use myList[c(3,2)]. We can extract a single observation from an element of a list by referencing it with a second square bracket, myList[[3]][2,] will return the second row from the third element of the list. Note here, that if you have a matrix or data.frame in your list that you reference it in matrix form [row,col]. Also note that we have to include the double square bracket to first extract the element from the list. To add another layer of complexity to lists, it is also possible to have named lists.

Other Useful Commands
If you will be working out of one directory, namely reading and writing files into one folder, it is handy to set your working directory using setwd("\user\path\"") so you dont have to re-write it every time you want to access an external file.

We havent used any R packages yet, but we will need some in future tutorials. In RStudio, you can use the drop down menu under Tools->Install Packages to install a local file (.zip, .gz) or browse the CRAN repository. If you know what package you wish to install, a simpler way is to enter install.packages("packagename") into the console.

If you need more information about any particular function, R provides extensive documentation that is accessible through ? or help() (e.g. ?read.table). If you are unsure of the exact function name, a fuzzy search using apropos() will return a list of functions with variations of the search name (e.g.apropos("matrix")).
